es and practices of the university reproduce interlocking systems of oppression that uphold racial capitalism, reproduce colonial relations, and promote settler nationalism. Critically engaging the work of Black learners, academics, organizers, and activists within this dynamic political context, this book underscores the importance of Black Studies across North America.  afunded by University of Toronto Libraries  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBlack peoplexStudy and teaching (Higher)zQuebec (Province)zMontreal. 0aCollege students, BlackzQuebec (Province)zMontreal. 0aCollege teachers, BlackzQuebec (Province)zMontreal. 0aDiscrimination in higher educationzQuebec (Province)zMontreal. 0aEducational sociologyzQuebec (Province)zMontreal. 0aRace relations. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh  aCanadian studies.  aMcGill University.  aQuébec.  aanticolonialism.  ablack students.  ablack studies.  acritical race theory.  ainstitutional ethnography.  asettler colonialism.  auniversities.2 aUniversity of Toronto Librariesefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311127253508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781487539528zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487539528zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487539528/original  a978-3-11-069045-3 University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-127253-5 ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  a